    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Earning A's in People Skills at Andover'' (front page, June 10):</p>
        <p>I find it paradoxical that the governor of a state in which affirmative action is under such heavy attack is himself the beneficiary of one of the most insidious forms of the practice: the ''legacy'' system, through which the children of the elite are admitted into competitive schools and colleges, fraternities and private clubs.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Earning A's in People Skills at Andover'' (front page, June 10):</p>
        <p>I find it paradoxical that the governor of a state in which affirmative action is under such heavy attack is himself the beneficiary of one of the most insidious forms of the practice: the ''legacy'' system, through which the children of the elite are admitted into competitive schools and colleges, fraternities and private clubs.</p>
        <p>Your article says that ''Yale, like Andover, gave a helping hand to alumni sons in the admission process . . . and it seems unlikely that Mr. Bush would have been admitted into Yale otherwise.'' For the white and the rich, it was called a ''helping hand''; for minorities, it is called affirmative action and is in danger, especially in states led by the brothers Bush.</p>
        <p>MARILYN KISS  Staten Island, June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
